  <h1>Common Burn Injury Claim Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>Burn-injury cases are among the most complex catastrophic injury matters &mdash; combining serious acute medicine, years of reconstructive surgery, disfigurement damages, and (in many cases) product-liability complexity. Patients and families often arrive at the legal process with significant misunderstandings. This guide addresses the most common.</p>

  <h2>1. "The case will settle quickly &mdash; I'll have money in a few months"</h2>
  <p><strong>Usually wrong.</strong> Burn cases typically take 18&ndash;36 months from injury to final resolution; severe burn cases run longer because the reconstructive-surgery roadmap takes 12&ndash;24 months to clarify and scars need that long to mature. Defendants and insurers rarely settle large burn cases quickly &mdash; they want to see how the burn evolves, what the final scar character looks like, and what the reconstructive needs really are. Settling too early locks the case at a value that doesn't reflect actual long-term needs.</p>

  <h2>2. "Any personal injury attorney can handle a burn case"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Burn cases require specialized expertise. General personal injury attorneys may not have:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Experience reviewing burn-center medical records and the burn-medicine literature on prognosis.</li>
    <li>Access to qualified burn life-care planners and reconstructive-surgery experts.</li>
    <li>Capacity to litigate complex product-liability burn cases (often requires significant upfront investment in fire-cause investigators, materials engineers, and design experts).</li>
    <li>Familiarity with disfigurement damages as a separate damages category.</li>
    <li>Multi-defendant case management experience (manufacturer, distributor, retailer in product cases).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Hiring the wrong attorney can substantially reduce recovery. Burn injury is a specialty within catastrophic injury practice.</p>

  <h2>3. "The insurance company will pay all my medical bills"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Health insurance pays only the amount they've negotiated with providers, not the billed amount. They have lifetime caps in some plans. They have exclusions for experimental treatments, out-of-network burn-center transfers, certain reconstructive procedures (insurers often categorize burn reconstruction as "cosmetic"), and psychiatric care beyond limited sessions. Workers' compensation has a separate, often-restrictive system. The civil case is what bridges the gap &mdash; recovering the full reasonable medical costs and the future reconstructive needs that no insurance covers.</p>

  <h2>4. "Burn reconstruction is cosmetic and not really compensable"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Burn reconstruction is a legitimate medical specialty addressing functional and aesthetic restoration after disfiguring injury. Insurance companies often reject reconstructive procedures as "cosmetic" to avoid coverage, but in litigation the reasonable cost of all medically-indicated reconstructive procedures is recoverable. A life-care planner with burn-specific experience can document that contracture release, scar revision, tissue expansion, and free-flap reconstruction are medically necessary, not cosmetic. The legal standard is reasonable medical necessity, not insurance company definitions.</p>

  <h2>5. "I should accept the first settlement offer to avoid a long case"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Insurance adjusters routinely make low-ball "quick settlement" offers in the first weeks after a burn. These offers are often 10&ndash;20% of the case's actual value. Accepting locks the case at that amount; future medical complications (sepsis, graft loss, contracture development, hypertrophic scarring), deteriorating prognosis, and life-care plan adjustments can't be re-opened. The "long case" actually gets you many multiples of the early offer.</p>

  <h2>6. "Pain and suffering is unlimited &mdash; I'll get millions for a small burn"</h2>
  <p><strong>Sometimes, often not.</strong> Pain and suffering and disfigurement damages can be significant in burn cases &mdash; often $500K&ndash;$5M+ in moderate-to-severe cases &mdash; but they're constrained by jurisdiction (some states cap non-economic damages in medical malpractice cases), by insurance availability (settlement cannot exceed what the defendant can pay), and by liability strength. A minor burn with full healing and minimal scarring will typically produce modest pain-and-suffering damages even with clear liability.</p>

  <h2>7. "Workers' compensation is the only recovery for workplace burns"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Most states have workers' comp exclusivity against the employer, but allow third-party claims against other parties &mdash; equipment manufacturers (defective machinery that caused the burn), chemical manufacturers (defective container or warning), premises owners (where not the employer), and other non-employer parties whose negligence contributed. A workplace burn case can yield workers' comp benefits PLUS a third-party recovery. The third-party recovery is often the larger of the two, particularly in product-liability scenarios.</p>

  <h2>8. "If the at-fault party has no insurance, I have no recovery"</h2>
  <p><strong>Often wrong.</strong> Even when the at-fault individual has no insurance:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Your own homeowners' or renters' insurance may have medical-payments coverage applicable to some accidents.</li>
    <li>If the at-fault party was working at the time, the employer's insurance may apply (vicarious liability).</li>
    <li>If a defective product contributed, the manufacturer, distributor, and retailer may all be liable.</li>
    <li>If a fire-code violation contributed, the landlord and (sometimes) municipal fire-inspection authority may be liable.</li>
    <li>For house fires, the landlord's insurance, the property manager's coverage, the contractor who did recent electrical work, and the appliance manufacturer all may apply.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>An experienced burn-injury attorney identifies all potentially liable parties and insurance sources.</p>

  <h2>9. "The attorney takes most of the money"</h2>
  <p><strong>Misleading.</strong> Burn-injury attorneys typically work on contingency at 33&ndash;40% of recovery. On a $3M settlement, the attorney's share is around $1M&ndash;$1.2M; the client's share is $1.8M&ndash;$2M. The attorney's fee also covers the case costs (experts, depositions, exhibits, life-care planner fees, burn-medicine and reconstructive-surgery experts) which in burn product-liability cases easily exceed $150K. Without the attorney, the client gets nothing or far less. The contingency math heavily favors retention.</p>

  <h2>10. "Settlements are tax-free"</h2>
  <p><strong>Mostly true, with exceptions.</strong> Compensatory damages for physical injury are excluded from taxable income under IRC &sect; 104(a)(2). But punitive damages are taxable, post-judgment interest is taxable, and emotional distress damages not arising from physical injury are taxable. Structured settlements paid over time may have specific tax treatment. Consult a tax professional for specific situations.</p>

  <h2>11. "Disfigurement damages and pain-and-suffering are the same thing"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong in most states.</strong> Most states treat disfigurement as a separate damages category, distinct from general pain-and-suffering. Valuation depends on visibility, severity, age, and (in some cases) occupation. Recognizing disfigurement separately tends to increase total non-economic damages in burn cases. A jury instructed to separately consider disfigurement &mdash; in addition to pain, suffering, mental anguish, and loss of life enjoyment &mdash; typically returns higher total non-economic awards than one instructed only on general pain-and-suffering.</p>

  <h2>12. "Lump sum is better than structured settlement"</h2>
  <p><strong>Depends.</strong> Lump sum gives flexibility but requires careful financial management for a multi-year reconstructive surgery sequence. Structured settlement provides guaranteed periodic payments timed to expected future procedures and reduces tax exposure, but has less flexibility. Many burn settlements use a combination: portion paid as lump sum for immediate needs (home modifications, lost wages caught up), portion structured for the upcoming reconstructive sequence over 3&ndash;5 years. The right structure depends on family circumstances and the projected procedure timeline.</p>

  <h2>13. "Burn cases involve government caps that limit recovery"</h2>
  <p><strong>Mostly false for civil personal injury.</strong> Most states have NO damages caps for civil burn-injury cases. Caps apply primarily in medical malpractice contexts (e.g., Texas $250K non-economic cap in med mal, recently-modified California caps). For product liability, premises liability, and standard negligence cases, recovery is typically uncapped. Disfigurement damages, where treated as a separate category, are usually outside any non-economic cap that exists.</p>

  <h2>14. "Punitive damages are guaranteed in cases of clear negligence"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Punitive damages require a higher standard than ordinary negligence &mdash; typically "gross negligence," "reckless disregard," or "willful misconduct." Common availability in burn cases: manufacturer concealment of known fire risk (lithium battery cases with documented internal awareness), repeat fire-code violations by a landlord, intentional safety violations by an employer with prior OSHA citations. Routine negligence cases (even with severe burns) typically do not include punitive damages.</p>

  <h2>15. "I should wait until the burns heal to consult an attorney"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Statutes of limitations are running, evidence is disappearing, and witnesses' memories are fading. An attorney can preserve evidence (litigation-hold letters, surveillance footage requests, scene preservation, product preservation), coordinate insurance disputes, and protect deadlines while the family focuses on medical care. There's no out-of-pocket cost (contingency fee), so there's no downside to early consultation. The case develops better with an attorney involved from the early weeks &mdash; not after months of evidence loss.</p>

  <h2>Bonus: "Modern medicine can fully restore appearance after a serious burn"</h2>
  <p><strong>Limited.</strong> Despite enormous advances in reconstructive surgery, severe burns typically produce permanent visible changes. Modern techniques (free flaps, tissue expansion, fractional laser, cultured epidermal autografts) can dramatically improve appearance and function compared to a generation ago, but "fully restoring" pre-injury appearance is not the realistic standard. Litigation should be based on realistic medical prognosis from a reconstructive surgery expert, not on hope for complete cosmetic restoration.</p>

  <h2>Bottom line</h2>
  <p>Burn-injury compensation works on a different scale than typical personal injury. The single-most-important variable is engaging experienced burn-injury counsel early. The contingency-fee structure means there's no out-of-pocket cost; the attorney's expertise (and access to the right experts) multiplies the recovery substantially. The most common claimant mistake is delaying the legal consultation while focused entirely on medical care &mdash; or, equally costly, accepting a quick low-ball settlement before the burn's full impact is known.</p>
